// Booking System JDL
entity Appointment {
startTime Instant required,
endTime Instant required,
status AppointmentStatus required
}
entity Service {
name String required minlength(3) maxlength(50),
description TextBlob,
price BigDecimal required min(0)
}
enum AppointmentStatus {
REQUESTED, // New status for initial booking request
SCHEDULED, // After admin approval
COMPLETED,
CANCELLED
}
relationship ManyToOne {
Appointment{user(login) required} to User with builtInEntity,
Appointment{service(name)} to Service
}
service Appointment, Service with serviceClass
paginate Appointment, Service with pagination
dto Appointment, Service with mapstruct
//**Explanation of Changes (and why there aren't many):**
//The user story update primarily describes *business logic* and *UI/UX* changes, not data model changes.  The addition of the `REQUESTED` status in the original prompt was already the most significant data-related change to support the admin approval workflow.
//Here's why the JDL remains largely the same:
//* **No New Entities:** The user story doesn't introduce new data objects that require their own entities.  Concepts like "approval status" are already handled by the `AppointmentStatus` enum.
//* **No New Relationships:** The relationships between `Appointment`, `Service`, and `User` are sufficient to model the described booking process.
//* **No Modified Entities/Relationships:** The existing entities and their attributes capture the necessary information (time, service, user, status).
//The core changes for the updated user story (email notifications, cancellation logic, preventing overlaps, admin approval actions) will be implemented in the service layer and controllers of your JHipster application, not in the JDL.  The JDL defines the *data structure*, while the application code defines the *behavior*.
//**Key Improvements in this Version:**
//* **Clarity in `AppointmentStatus`:** I've added a comment to clarify that `SCHEDULED` represents the state after admin approval. This makes the enum's purpose clearer.
//This revised JDL provides a solid foundation for implementing the updated user story's requirements. Remember that the bulk of the work will be in your Java/TypeScript code to handle the business rules and user interface interactions.